{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_20","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,240p' papers/README.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Downloaded Papers\n\n## Primary Papers\n\n1. [XSTest: A Test Suite for Identifying Exaggerated Safety Behaviours in Large Language Models](2308.01263_xstest.pdf)\n   - Authors: Paul Rottger, Hannah Rose Kirk, Bertie Vidgen, Giuseppe Attanasio, Federico Bianchi, Dirk Hovy\n   - Year: 2023\n   - Source: arXiv / NAACL 2024\n   - Why relevant: Core benchmark for benign false-refusal and exaggerated safety.\n\n2. [Fine-tuning Aligned Language Models Compromises Safety, Even When Users Do Not Intend To!](2310.03693_finetuning_compromises_safety.pdf)\n   - Authors: Xiangyu Qi, Yi Zeng, Tinghao Xie, Pin-Yu Chen, Ruoxi Jia, Prateek Mittal, Peter Henderson\n   - Year: 2023\n   - Source: arXiv\n   - Why relevant: Shows narrow fine-tuning can perturb safety behavior even with benign data.\n\n3. [Refusal in Language Models Is Mediated by a Single Direction](2406.11717_refusal_single_direction.pdf)\n   - Authors: Andy Arditi, Oscar Obeso, Aaquib Syed, Daniel Paleka, Nina Panickssery, Wes Gurnee, Neel Nanda\n   - Year: 2024\n   - Source: arXiv / NeurIPS 2024\n   - Why relevant: Strong mechanistic evidence that adding a refusal direction can induce refusals on harmless prompts.\n\n4. [WildGuard: Open One-Stop Moderation Tools for Safety Risks, Jailbreaks, and Refusals of LLMs](2406.18495_wildguard.pdf)\n   - Authors: Seungju Han, Kavel Rao, Allyson Ettinger, Liwei Jiang, Bill Yuchen Lin, Nathan Lambert, Yejin Choi, Nouha Dziri\n   - Year: 2024\n   - Source: arXiv / NeurIPS 2024 Datasets and Benchmarks\n   - Why relevant: Provides refusal detection tooling and the WildGuardMix moderation dataset.\n\n5. [Surgical, Cheap, and Flexible: Mitigating False Refusal in Language Models via Single Vector Ablation](2410.03415_false_refusal_vector_ablation.pdf)\n   - Authors: Xinpeng Wang, Chengzhi Hu, Paul Rottger, Barbara Plank\n   - Year: 2024\n   - Source: arXiv\n   - Why relevant: Follow-up intervention paper directly targeted at false refusal.\n\n6. [Emergent Misalignment: Narrow finetuning can produce broadly misaligned LLMs](2502.17424_emergent_misalignment.pdf)\n   - Authors: Jan Betley, Daniel Tan, Niels Warncke, Anna Sztyber-Betley, Xuchan Bao, Martin Soto, Nathan Labenz, Owain Evans\n   - Year: 2025\n   - Source: arXiv\n   - Why relevant: Important analogue for the hypothesis that narrow fine-tuning can generalize into broad behavioral changes.\n\n7. [Think Before Refusal: Triggering Safety Reflection in LLMs to Mitigate False Refusal Behavior](2503.17882_think_before_refusal.pdf)\n   - Authors: Shengyun Si, Xinpeng Wang, Guangyao Zhai, Nassir Navab, Barbara Plank\n   - Year: 2025\n   - Source: arXiv / OpenReview\n   - Why relevant: Tests a training intervention specifically aimed at reducing false refusal while preserving safety.\n\n8. [COVER: Context-Driven Over-Refusal Verification in LLMs](2025_findings_acl_1243_cover.pdf)\n   - Authors: Giovanni Sullutrone, Riccardo Amerigo Vigliermo, Sonia Bergamaschi, Luca Sala\n   - Year: 2025\n   - Source: ACL Findings 2025\n   - Why relevant: Extends over-refusal evaluation into contextual/RAG-style settings.\n\n## Supplemental Papers Present in Workspace\n\n- `2307.02483_Jailbroken.pdf`\n- `2308.06995_XSTest.pdf`\n- `2312.13540_SODE.pdf`\n- `2402.04249_HarmBench.pdf`\n- `2404.01318_JailbreakBench.pdf`\n- `2406.00907_OR-Bench.pdf`\n- `2407.11969_Past_Tense_Refusal.pdf`\n- `2408.08272_PHTest.pdf`\n\nThese supplemental PDFs were present in `papers/` during this run. They were not the primary focus of the review, but several are useful follow-on benchmarks for the experiment runner.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
